<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-380-380  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 380 380.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>3D  August 1990 n28 p42(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font wars. (what the font fights are all about)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Atkin, Gavin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The development of different fonts by various software publisherscould have implications for users of digital type.andP;  Softwarepublishers claim that their fonts will be compatible, but usersstill may end up having to choose between competing standards.andO;Microsoft's word processing packages, for example, use their owntype of font.andP;  Adobe's PostScript has two types of fonts: Type 1,whose specifications allow hinting and manipulation; and Type 3,whose specifications do not.andP;  Letraset designed its own pagelayout and type manipulation packages after determining that thePostScript font was not appropriate for its needs.andP;  Apple andMicrosoft have developed the TrueType page description language,claiming that it will be an open product.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Adobe Systems Inc. (Products)Microsoft Corp. (Products)Apple Computer Inc. (Products)Letraset USA (Products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; MSFT; ADBE.andO;Product:   PostScript (Printer software) (Design and construction).andO;Topic:     FontsSoftware PublishersPage Description LanguagesDesktop Publishing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>